# Cyberland — Mod patterns (HDR demo baseline)

Ship mods so they read like the repo’s best samples: **cold start** via a **private `SetupSceneAsync` on `Mod`** + **scene JSON**, then query-driven updates, real parallelism only, and clear folder boundaries.

## Scene setup (cold start)

**Standard (preferred for new and migrated mods):**

- Author entities in **`Content/Scenes/<name>.json`** (see **`RuntimeScenes/Serialization/SceneDocument`** and engine builtins such as **`cyberland.engine/transform`**).
- Register mod-specific component types from **`OnLoadAsync`** (or from the private setup helper) via **`context.Scenes.RegisterComponentDeserializer`** — see **`mods/Cyberland.Demo/SceneComponentDeserializers.cs`**.
- Add a **private** **`async ValueTask SetupSceneAsync(ModLoadContext context, CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)`** on **`Mod`** (same placement as other bootstrap helpers, not a separate public **`SceneSetup`** type).
- **Await it from `OnLoadAsync`** *before* **`context.RegisterSerial` / `RegisterParallel` / `RegisterSingleton`**, so entities exist before any **`OnStart`** / **`OnSingletonStart`** runs.
- Inside the helper: register deserializers, then **`await context.Scenes.SpawnIntoWorldAsync(context.World, "Content/Scenes/….json", cancellationToken: cancellationToken)`** into the **root** world. **`throw`** on failure; require **`context.Scenes`** and any host services the deserializers need (e.g. **`Renderer`** for texture ids).
- Use **`logicalId`** + **`parentLogicalId`** on transforms when hierarchies must be wired at spawn time.
- Keep **`async`** / **`cancellationToken`** even when the body is mostly registration + one spawn call—additive **`BeginLoad`** + **`PumpAsync`** paths may grow later.
- After spawn, **do not** wire entities with **`LogicalActorLookup.Resolve`** and hardcoded GUID strings in mod code — use **scene tags** + **`RequireSingleEntityWith<T>`** (see **cyberland-demo-mod-authoring** § *Wiring spawned entities*).

**Additive worlds (optional):**

- **`ISceneRuntime.BeginLoad`** allocates extra **`World` + `SystemScheduler`** pairs; the **host** pumps **`PumpAsync`** on the render tick. Kick off loads from **`OnLoadAsync`** without awaiting long GPU work (same deadlock rules as MSDF async load).

**Legacy (avoid for new work):**

- A separate **static `SceneSetup`** class beside **`Mod.cs`** — fold cold start into **`Mod`** + JSON instead.
- A spawn-only **`ISystem`** with **`OnStart`** and no phase hooks—migrate so the scheduler lists **runtime** systems only.
- Large C# spawn tables when the same data can live in scene JSON + deserializers.

**Always:**

- Split **runtime** systems by responsibility (input, simulate, lights-fill, HUD); **do not** scatter spawn code across multiple **`OnStart`** handlers or phase updates.

## UI setup (retained HUD)

- Author trees in **`Content/Ui/*.json`**; link from scene via **`ui-document-root.data.uiPath`**.
- Use stable element **`id`** strings for post-spawn binding (**`UiDocuments.TryGetElements`** + **`UiElementLookup.Require<T>`**).
- Engine types: **`IUiRuntime`** / **`context.Ui`**, **`EngineUiElementDeserializers`**, **`UiBuildResult`** — see **cyberland-ui-json-authoring**.
- **`mods/Cyberland.Demo*`:** JSON-only UI trees (no **`new UiDocument()`** in mod code). Non-demo mods may still prototype UI in C# until migrated.

## Scheduler / host contract

- **`OnStart`** / **`OnSingletonStart`** runs **before** phase callbacks for that registration; treat required host services and entities as **available**. Validate impossible configuration with **`throw`** and clear messages—do not soften failures into silent skips.
- **Do not** use `_initialized` / `_resolved` flags or **phase-update early returns** that mean “maybe not ready yet.” Avoid defensive null checks on host services in hot paths when the mod **requires** those services to function (use non-null assertion when the contract guarantees presence).
- First-frame lazy init inside **`*Update`** is forbidden (see **cyberland-mod-system-lifecycle**).

## Queries and stores

- **`IEcsQuerySource.QuerySpec`** / **`SystemQuerySpec`** is the **single declaration** of what the scheduler loads each phase.
- **Phase updates** iterate **`ChunkQueryAll`** (serial **`ISystem`**) or parallel chunk views (**`IParallelSystem`**)—**that is the hot path** for multi-row work.
- **Do not** cache **`Components<T>()`** stores on the system as fields for ongoing use, and **do not** replace scheduler queries with broad store scans unless there is a deliberate, documented reason.
- **`World`** may be cached in **`OnStart`** when **random access** is required (`DestroyEntity`, ad-hoc queries). For **exactly one entity** that owns the system’s work, prefer **`ISingletonSystem`** (below) so phase hooks take **`SingletonEntity`** instead of chunk iteration. Follow **cyberland-ecs-world-access**.

## Singleton rows — prefer `ISingletonSystem`

Use **`context.RegisterSingleton`** with **`ISingletonSystem`** when **exactly one** entity matches **`QuerySpec`** and the system exists to drive **that row** (player, session state, a single HUD **`BitmapText`** row, fullscreen **`PostProcessVolumeSource`**, etc.).

- Implement **`ISingletonEarlyUpdate`**, **`ISingletonFixedUpdate`**, and/or **`ISingletonLateUpdate`** as needed; callbacks receive **`in SingletonEntity`** with **`Get<T>()`** / **`TryGet<T>`** for **mutable** component access on the resolved entity—**no** **`ChunkQueryAll`**.
- **`OnSingletonStart(in SingletonEntity)`** runs once after resolution; use it for one-time placement, validation, and caching **other** **`EntityId`**s only when the system **must** read a second archetype (see **`HdrPostVolumeFillSystem`**: volume is the singleton query; player id resolved once for bloom follow).
- Do **not** use **`SystemQuerySpec.Empty`** with ad-hoc **`World`** queries for the primary row when a non-empty **`QuerySpec`** + **`ISingletonSystem`** would describe the same entity—register a singleton instead.

**Chunk iteration for a single row (legacy / rare):** a serial **`ISystem`** may still set **`QuerySpec`** to the singleton archetype and use **`GetFirst<T>()`** on **`ChunkQueryAll`**—but **`ISingletonSystem`** is clearer and matches engine scheduling docs. Reserve **`ISystem` + chunk `GetFirst`** for cases where you intentionally keep the chunk API without migrating yet.

## Parallel systems

- Prefer **`IParallelSystem`** when work **partitions rows/chunks** with **`Parallel.ForEach`**, span splitting, or equivalent **real** concurrency (**`ParallelOptions`** from the host).
- **Do not** register **`IParallelSystem`** implementations that only use a plain **`foreach`** with no real parallel work—use **`ISystem`** + **`RegisterSerial`** or **`ISingletonSystem`** + **`RegisterSingleton`** instead (honest scheduling; avoids misleading readers).

## Folder layout (per mod assembly)

- **`Components/`** — `struct` **`IComponent`** types, tag markers, mod-local tuning/constants structs.
- **`Systems/`** — **`ISystem`**, **`IParallelSystem`**, and **`ISingletonSystem`** implementations only (plus nested private helpers if kept tiny).
- **`Content/Scenes/`** — versioned scene JSON for root spawn and/or additive loads.
- **`Mod.cs`** at mod root with **private** cold-start helper + **`OnLoadAsync`**; optional **`*InputSetup.cs`** / **`*SceneComponentDeserializers.cs`** beside **`IMod`** when bindings or JSON types stay centralized.

## Comments and formatting

- Type-level **`///`** summaries + **`remarks`** where they teach **why** and **phase ordering** (see HDR **`Mod.cs`** and motion/post systems).
- **Inline `//`** for non-obvious intent, coordinate conventions, struct copy-back, or threading—not narration of syntax.
- Keep formatting consistent with solution defaults (readable wraps, no cramped one-liners for multi-step logic).

